# 📅 Week 4 — Experimental Design

## 🗣️ Explain It Like I'm 5

Before you collect ANY data, you need to plan your experiment properly.
A bad experiment design = bad data = wrong conclusions. No amount of fancy statistics can fix that.

**The key ideas:**

**Randomisation** — randomly assign subjects to treatment groups.
> Why? To make sure the groups are fair. If you always put the healthiest people in the treatment group, your results will be biased.

**Replication** — repeat the experiment multiple times.
> Why? One measurement is unreliable. The more you measure, the closer you get to the truth.

**Blocking** — group similar subjects together, then randomise within blocks.
> Example: If you're testing a drug, you might block by gender first — then randomly assign men to treatments and women to treatments separately. This removes the effect of gender from your error.

**Completely Randomised Design (CRD)** — the simplest design. Just randomly assign subjects to groups. All treatments are equally likely for all subjects.

**Factorial Design** — test multiple factors at the same time.
> Example: Testing 3 drugs (factor A) × with/without vitamin C (factor B) = 6 treatment combinations. This is efficient AND lets you see if the factors *interact* with each other.

> 💡 ANOVA (coming up in Weeks 5-7) is the statistical test used for these designs.

---

## 📌 Key Ideas Cheat Sheet

- **Randomisation** = removes bias
- **Replication** = reduces variability, increases reliability
- **Blocking** = controls for a known nuisance variable
- **CRD** = simplest: randomly assign to groups
- **Factorial design** = test all combinations of 2+ factors
- One-way ANOVA → **one** factor | Two-way ANOVA → **two** factors

